    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1466620110" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1466620110" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5143619-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546601194p2/5143619.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1466620110?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/5143619-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1466620110" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10430719714494503178">In 1692, while much of Europe was reeling under the murderous deeds of the Inquisition, it would be on the other side of the Atlantic were the Puritans of New England in America would have there own &apos;dance with evil&apos;. It all began in the village of Salem in Massachusetts, when the daughter and niece of clergyman, Reverend Samuel Parris, started convulsing and having fits. After being examined by a local doctor, the only possible explanation was that the girls conditions were likely caused by wit</span>
  <span id="freeText10430719714494503178" style="display:none">In 1692, while much of Europe was reeling under the murderous deeds of the Inquisition, it would be on the other side of the Atlantic were the Puritans of New England in America would have there own 'dance with evil'. It all began in the village of Salem in Massachusetts, when the daughter and niece of clergyman, Reverend Samuel Parris, started convulsing and having fits. After being examined by a local doctor, the only possible explanation was that the girls conditions were likely caused by witchcraft.<br /><br />Afterwards the two girls would set the stones for the whole sorry saga when they named Parris household slave, Tituba and local women Sarah Good and Sarah Osborn as witches who had cast spells on them. All three women would be brought to court in what would be called sham trials these days. The line of questioning virtually assumed guilt with the only only way to avoid the death penelty being to admit guilt. Tituba made things even worse in admitting she made a pact with the devil, had flown on a broomstick and had pointed the finger at Good and Osborn.<br /><br />These revelations would cause all hell to break out as over the next couple of months residents began accusing one another at an alarming rate. Hearsay was all that was required for someone to be brought before the courts and for those that refused to admit guilt, a date with the hangman's noose was there fate. All up some 150 local men and women would end up in prison awaiting trial and tragically fourteen women, five men and two dogs would be executed having been found guilty of witchcraft. Only in October that year did the madness end when Governor William Phipps disbanded the courts, with prisoners released and those marked to be executed pardoned.<br /><br />Author Stacy Schiff does a good job in trying to explain why such a gruesome period could happen. Witchcraft was nothing new back then having gone back centuries in Europe, while it was also true the colonialists had lived in fear for years from the native Indians and used there rigid religious standards that feared witches and witchcraft to punish those who acted unusually. These days mental illness is well known but back then the only explanation for the Parris girls action was seen as being possessed. The only good that came out of this period was that such an event would never happen again and as a side note other than the Suffragette movement and the time of prohibition, would be the only time when women would be a part of significant change in US history. Well written and thoroughly researched, The Witches: Salem, 1692 is highly recommended for anyone who is interested in one of history's darkest periods.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10430719714494503178" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


